===Etymology===
Related to {{term|Ruthene|lang=en}}, {{term|Ruthenian|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|Rutheni|lang=la}}, {{term|Ruteni|lang=la}}, related to {{term|Russi|lang=la}}, {{term|Ruzi|lang=la}} as {{term|Prutheni|lang=la}}, {{term|Pruteni|lang=la}} is to {{term|Prussi|lang=la}}, {{term|Pruzi||[[Prussian]]s|lang=la}}.  Compare {{term|Rus}}, {{term|Russ}}, from Old East Slavic {{term|Русь|tr=Rus’|sc=Cyrl|lang=orv}}, compare medieval Greek {{term|οί Ῥῶς|tr=oi Rhos|sc=Grek|lang=gkm}}.

===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun}}

# The territory of [[Eastern Europe]] inhabited by [[Rusyn]]s, on the slopes of the Carpathian Mountains in parts of Ukraine, Poland and Slovakia.
# {{context|historical|lang=en}} Lands inhabited by Ukrainians ([[Ruthenian]]s) of the former Austrian Empire kingdom of [[Galicia]] (1772–1918), corresponding to parts of Western Ukraine.
# {{context|historical|lang=en}} Western East-Slavic lands, including the principalities of Halych-Volynia and Kiev, which united with Lithuania and Poland (14th c–1772), corresponding to parts of Belarus and Ukraine.
# {{context|historical|lang=en}} [[Rus]], an East Slavic medieval state (880–12th c), corresponding to parts of Belarus, Russia, and Ukraine.
# [[Russia]] (''Latin'')

